\nwhen it unanimously held that the Boeing Company violated\nthe law in refusing to deal with I.A.M. Aeronautical District.\n751 during the strike at Seattle last year.\nNot only did the Circuit Court slap down the Labor Board,\ntrial, which it was not,\nbut it proceeded to put the union\nand went so far as to -|uestion the Board s good faith.\nThe Court s decision shows the truthfulness of Mr. Hartley's\nThere is plenty more to this law than meets the\non\nconfession.\neye.\nThe Taft-Hartley Act requires that the union give 60 days\nnotice to the employer when it seeks to end or to change an\nThat was to guarantee the employer a\nI\nexisting agreement.\nasonable period for negotiations, a 60-day period,\nlion, the Act requires the union to give 30 days notice to the\nConciliation Service if no agreement is reached. T he Con\nwho voted for this law said they wanted to give the\nIn addi\ngressmen\nConciliators a chance to settle a dispute before a strike had\nreasonable period of negotiations and after\nunion members supposed\nstarted. After a\nconciliation had been attempted, the\nly were to be free to strike. Supposedly, that is.\nThe conservative Circuit Court now holds, in the Boeing\nthat it isn't enough to put the employer on notice months\nIt isn't enough that\n'\u25a0ase,\nin advance that the contract has expired.\n'he employer has recognized the expiration and made his own\npioposals for a new contract in writing months before the\ntrike. It isn't enough that union and company representatives\negoliations for 16 long months before 1\nIt isn't enough that the union has called in J\nhave been in fruitless n\ntne strike starts,\nthe Federal Conciliators and that they have tried and failed\nIt isn't enough that the union has offered 1\ndispute.\nto adjust the dispute,\nto arbitrate all differences in\nUnder the Taft-Hartley Act, according to this Circuit Court, j\nstrike may be declared illegal unless the union has given the\nrtnployer 60 days notice of the dale on which it intends to\nNo such requirement appears in the language of the\nTaft-Hartley Act. Yet, without such notice by the union, this\ncourt holds, the Taft-Hartley Act permits any employer to hire\nscabs and to try to re-open any plant by force.\na\nstrike.\ns nothing else, it has\nm Congress aware of the\nIt has reinforced the\nIf the Boeing decision accomplish!\nhelped to make the men and women\nvengeful spirit of the Taft-Hartley Act\ndrive for Taft-Hartley repeal.\nWAR'S WORST LABOR SMEAR A h AKE A.P.' ADMITS\nMore than six years after it transmitted lar and wide one of\nar, the \"Associated Press\nthe worst anti-labor smears o I the w\nItnally retracted this week.\nThe smear hit the headlines back\nSeamen\u2014so the story said\nwith supplies to the war\ntoon Islands.\nUnion\nin January, 1943.\nbrought a merchant ship loaded\n\u2022torn port of Guadalcanal in\nthe Solo\n\nSunday\u2014so the story said\u2014they\n(using to unload ahy of the supplies, 1\nThen, because it was a\nstaged a\n\"forcing w\n-Some unnamed marines\n\u00abbarge.\n\"sit-down\n\u2022ounded and hungry Marines to finish the job.\nwere given as \"authority\" for the\nI c\nAs Labor reported at the time, high officials of the Navy\npromptly called the story a fake. It never happened, they said\nand in fact, couldn t have happened because seamen don l\ns done by longshoremen at each\nThat'\nunload ships anyway,\nport, and the Navy had Seabees\" to do the job in Guadalcanal.\n.Seamen are kept busy\n.Maritime Union, which was named in\non other tasks aboard ship. I he National\nthe story, branded it as\na bald lie.\nf the hubbub, the \"A.P.\" carried no i\nNow after six years the big press service finally\nDuring the height o\ncorrection,\napologized.\n\"A thorough investigation conducted at the instance\nof the Associated Press has produced no evidence attributing\nfuch conduct or such an incident to any National Maritime 1\ncrew\", it said.\nOnly\nthe\n\"settled 1\n$8.300 in'\nke amends at this late date?\nthe Maritime Union had sued it for libel and was on\nSo the press service\nrun the retraction\u2014and paying\nWhy did the A.P.\nin\nbecause\nay to winning in the courts,\nby agreeing to\nto the union.\ndamages\n\\V<* Don't Patronize\nin* Grocery Hto\u00bb'*a\nTli\u00ae Kollo\n\u00abH l hr y have refused to comply\nwith the 8: OU P.M Sunday -nd\nHoliday CLOSING Agreement\nECONOMICAL G KOCEIt Y\nHO S. Mont. SI\nMIX I (JHOCEHV\n21U S. Mont St\n<20 Went Galena\nWALSH\nWe would re.peclfully regue.t\nmembers of organised labor and\nI heir frleud# to Co-operate with\nthe Kutte Clerk'\u00ab Union and die\nlontlnue their patronage\nKNDORUBU. BY THE SILVEIt\nHOW 1 HADES AND LABOR\nCOUNCIL\n\nBUTTE BUILDING AND\nCONSTRUCTION\nTRADES COUNCIL\n(We Do Not Patronize List)\nLEE S TRAILER SALES\u20142701\nHarrison\nJOE TORPEY, PLASTERER\nSouth of lhe C itv.\nMR. R NELSON\u2014S0-, Majors\nStreet\nWALTER ARNOLD\u2014 F orincr\nOwner of Arnold Plnmhing Co.\n(Not the Walter Arnold,\nAn hit\u00ab t.J\nP. J. HA NH ATT Y \u2014Caledonia\nand Jackson Streets.\nHENRY\nand First Streets.\nArizona\nGIROUX\nGuilder.\nJOHN MARKOVICH \u2014I iome\nbuilder.\n\u25a0orge Street.\nKENNETH\nV47 W.\nI'hmihing Co.\nv<X-*X\n(Home\n2123\nAildress\n\nPARMALEE\nWind man, Parmalee\n3ET \"''iTi.lt-'F 1 1 J: J\nJ\nKXLF PROGRAM SCHEDULE\nP AVISO TIME\nDAYl ir.nr\nNil A Y\nRo.ndup\nOrd\n8 15 SI\nI of MUSIC\n,al Radio Pulpit\nMelodies\nH :\u00ab0 Came\nSat\niH)\nan\nFut nl\nI tonal\ni Serenade\nLite*\nfor Young Sclentl is\nIntern\nin if Moi\n10 30 New\nIII\n11 00 Living 1941*\n11 30 public- Affaire\n11 45 Report\nNBC Symphony\n\u2022s Down the Wind\nNBC University The\u00bbin\nFamily\n10 4\nEurope\n12 no\ni oo Vo\n1 30\n2 30 O\n3 00 Quiz Kids\n3 '30 N\n35 Jane Pickens Show\n4 00 RCA Victor Show\nM\nal Harvester Show\nHank Hi Lites ol Hist\u00bb\nkee Hoad News\nIntt\n5 00 Me\n5 30 Mil\n5 45\n00 Richard Diamond\nHarns-Allce Faye\nEmil Maruns Fashion Parade\nPhil\nf. 30\n7 00 Fred Allen\n7 30 Henry